<subSubSection lastPageId="239" lastPageNumber="240" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="238.[151,1436,1805,2009]" lastBlockId="239.[151,1436,151,212]" lastPageId="239" lastPageNumber="240" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1913,1938]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Dankittipakul &amp; Jocqué &amp; Singtripop, 2012" authorityName="Dankittipakul &amp; Jocqué &amp; Singtripop" authorityYear="2012" box="[328,555,1913,1937]" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Mallinella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pecularis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[328,555,1913,1937]" italics="true" pageId="238" pageNumber="239">Mallinella pecularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[562,648,1914,1937]" pageId="238" pageNumber="239" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be recognized by a lengthened epigastric stalk on the anterior part of the opisthosoma which reminds of a medially constricted body with a distinct petiole in most hymenopterans (Figs 1086, 1088–1089). The male palp can be easily distinguished by a depression on the expanded tegulum surrounded by several elevated ridges and by a basal extension on the retrolateral side of the cymbium (Figs 1092–1093).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
